{"title_page": "Corona del Mar High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name              =Corona del Mar High School \n|image             =CDM high school front entrance photo D Ramey Logan.jpg\n|caption           = Corona del Mar High School Front Entrance: April 2015\n|streetaddress     =2101 Eastbluff Drive \n|city              =[[Newport Beach, California|Newport Beach]] \n|state             =[[California]] \n|zipcode           =92660\n|coordinates       ={{Coord|33.633537|-117.876686|type:edu_region:US-CA|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|district          =[[Newport-Mesa Unified School District]]\n|principal         =Kathy Scott (9-12), Becky Gogel (7-8)   \n|type              =[[Public school (government funded)|Public]] \n|grades            = 7 - 12 \n|motto             = Cultivate Integrity, Develop Resiliency, Model Empathy\n|team_name         = Sea Kings, Sea Queens (high school)<br> Riptide (junior high school)\n|nickname          = Home of the Sea Kings\n|conference = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[CIF Southern Section|Southern Section]] <br/> [[Sunset League (California)|Sunset League]]\n|rival             = [[Newport Harbor High School|Newport Harbor]]\n|colors            = Navy, Columbia blue, Silver, White\n|established       = 1962 \n|ratio             = 25.61<ref name=NCES/>\n|teaching_staff    = 101.20 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|enrollment        = 2,592 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0627240&ID=062724004109|title=Corona del Mar High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|homepage          ={{URL|http://cdm.nmusd.us/}}\n}}\n\n'''Corona del Mar High School''' ('''CdM''') is a public school located in the Eastbluff neighborhood of [[Newport Beach, California]], and belongs to the [[Newport-Mesa Unified School District]].  It is a combination of a middle school (7th and 8th grades) and a high school (9th, 10th, 11th, and 12th grades). The school was founded in 1962 and has an enrollment of just over 2600 students. The school covers an area of just over 1,700,000 square feet. According to US News, there are 92 full-time teachers.\n\nIt has been ranked by ''[[Newsweek]]'' as one of the top 200 high schools in the United States,<ref name =newsweektop500/> and it has been a state champion in several sports. However, it has also been featured in the national media for scandals involving [[homophobia]], [[sexism]], and academic dishonesty.\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Corona Del Mar Middle School photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|The Corona Del Mar Middle School]]\nThe school was founded in 1962. In the mid 1970s, the school went through an extensive design process to develop its media center.<ref name=\"HanniganEstes1978\">{{cite book|last1=Hannigan|first1=Jane Anne|last2=Estes|first2=Glenn E.|title=Media Center Facilities Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAqfAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=October 15, 2014|year=1978|publisher=American Library Association|isbn=9780838932124}}</ref> The Marian Bergeson Aquatic Center, named for state senator [[Marian Bergeson]] who was from Newport Beach, opened in May 1990 at a cost of $1.75 million.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Belson|first1=Eve|title=Water Polo: Going for the Gold|journal=Orange Coast|date=February 1992|page=14 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4xEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=%22corona+del+mar+high+school%22+1990&source=bl&ots=_05sX_WvZt&sig=JA0UjRyfZRcqjC24HyebvZ7iNkU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=w80cVaGDNITnoATs_4FY&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22corona%20del%20mar%20high%20school%22%201990&f=false|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> In March 2015, a {{convert|29,000|sqft|adj=on}} performing arts center was finished. The center cost $16 million and seats more than 360 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corona del Mar High School Unveils New Theater at Ribbon-Cutting Ceremony|url=http://www.coronadelmartoday.com/48511/home/corona-del-mar-high-school-unveils-new-theater-at-ribbon-cutting-ceremony/|website=Corona del Mar Today|accessdate=April 1, 2015|date=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907201559/http://www.coronadelmartoday.com/48511/home/corona-del-mar-high-school-unveils-new-theater-at-ribbon-cutting-ceremony/|archive-date=September 7, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nicolai|first1=Megan|title=Corona del Mar schools unveil $16 million performing arts center|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/school-654134-arts-high.html|work=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=March 13, 2015|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2009 and 2014 Corona del Mar was the subject of a series of controversies concerning [[sexism]] and [[homophobia]]. In February 2009, when a production of the musical [[Rent (musical)|''Rent'']] was cancelled, the theater teacher alleged it was due to the principal objecting to the play's depiction of homosexuality.<ref>[http://www.ocregister.com/articles/school-111922-gay-asrani.html \"Instructor: Play canceled because of gay characters\"], by Jeff Overley, [[Orange County Register]], February 13, 2009</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Rent\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/20/theater/20rent.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1320105752-tii0ffIkGckeG7XOoNOY4Q \"Tamer 'Rent' Is Too Wild for Some Schools\"], by Patrick Healy, ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 19, 2009</ref><ref name=\"Advocate\">[http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/02/27/canceled-high-school-production-rent-back \"Canceled High School Production of Rent Back On\"], by Ross von Metzke, ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', February 27, 2009</ref>  Student demand eventually brought back the play.<ref name=\"Advocate\" /> The following month, after a video surfaced of male students threatening to rape and kill a female peer, the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] sued the school for inadequately responding to, allowing, and even condoning an atmosphere of sexist and homophobic violence.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/19/local/me-aclu-school-suit19 \"ACLU sues Corona del Mar High School for cultivating 'homophobic' environment\"], by Susannah Rosenblatt, [[Los Angeles Times]], March 19, 2009</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/19/theater/19arts-ACLUSUESSCHO_BRF.html?_r=1 \"A.C.L.U. Sues School Involved in 'Rent' Tussle\"], by Patrick Healy, ''The New York Times'', March 18, 2009</ref> A [[settlement (litigation)|settlement]] was reached in September, when the District agreed to create and enforce anti-harassment policies and train both students and staff.<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/settlement-reached-in-california-high-school-rent-case/?hp \"Settlement Reached in California High School 'Rent' Case\"], by Patricia Cohen, ArtsBeat for ''The New York Times'', September 10, 2009</ref> In May 2014, the school again attracted negative attention for an [[National Football League draft|NFL-style]] \"prom draft\" in which female students were ceremonially \"drafted\" as dates by their male peers.<ref>[http://www.ocregister.com/articles/draft-612766-prom-school.html \"High school boys hold 'draft' to pick prom dates\"], by Lauren Steussy, ''[[Orange County Register]]'', May 5, 2014</ref><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/05/calif-high-school-students-accused-of-using-a-prom-draft-to-find-date/ \"Calif. High School Students Accused of Using a 'Prom Draft' to Find Date\"] by Tina Chen, [[American Broadcasting Company]], May 7, 2014</ref> Writers for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' cited a former Corona del Mar High School disciplinarian in their argument that the \"draft\" was the result of a problematic sense of entitlement among Newport Beach residents.<ref name=\"LATimes1\">[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-cdm-prom-draft-culture-20140507-story.html \"'Prom draft' reflects Newport Beach culture, ex-school official says\"] by Adolfo Flores, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', May 7, 2014</ref><ref name=\"LATimes2\">[http://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-0509-prom-draft-20140509-story.html \"School prom 'draft' prompts reflection in exclusive Newport Beach\"] by Adolfo Flores, [[Christopher Goffard]] and Hannah Fry, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', May 8, 2014</ref>\n\nThe school also experienced a series of publicized academic integrity incidents. In 2012, school officials discovered that ten students had bought the answers to their tests from [[Amazon.com]].<ref name=\"7signs\" /><ref>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2012/01/06/corona-del-mar-students-buy-test-banks-off-amazon-com/ \"Corona Del Mar Students Buy Test Banks Off Amazon.com\"], [[CBS]]-LA, January 6, 2012</ref> In early 2014, eleven Corona del Mar High School students were expelled<ref name=\"LATimes2\" /><ref>[http://abc7.com/archive/9411848/ \"Corona del Mar High School hacking: 11 students expelled\"], [[KABC-TV]], January 29, 2014</ref><ref name=\"CBSLA\">[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2014/11/04/tutor-pleads-not-guilty-in-newport-beach-school-hacker-scandal/ \"Tutor Pleads Not Guilty In O.C. School Hacker Scandal\"], [[CBS]]-LA, November 4, 2014</ref><ref name=\"DP\">[http://www.dailypilot.com/news/tn-dpt-me-1006-cdm-arrest-20141006,0,4452919.story \"Police arrest tutor in Corona del Mar High cheating scandal\"], by Hannah Fry, [[Daily Pilot]], October 6, 2014</ref><ref name=KPCC>[http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/10/07/47219/tutor-charged-in-corona-del-mar-high-school-grade/ \"Tutor charged in Corona del Mar High School grade scandal\"], [[Associated Press]]/[[KPCC]], October 7, 2014</ref><ref name=\"MyNewsLa\">[http://mynewsla.com/education/2014/10/07/tutor-alleged-corona-del-mar-cheating-scandal-arrested-lax/ \"Tutor in Alleged Corona Del Mar Cheating Scandal Arrested at LAX\"], by John Schreiber, [http://mynewsla.com/ My News LA], October 7, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.ocregister.com/articles/students-599284-school-accused.html?page=1 \"11 students removed from Corona del Mar High in hacking case\"], by Lauren Steussy, Melody Petersen, and Ryah Cooley, ''[[Orange County Register]]'', January 29, 2014</ref> for hacking into school computers with the help of a tutor to alter their grades.<ref>[http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2014/10/06/orange-county-tutor-charged-in-grade-scandal/ \"Orange County Tutor Charged In Grade Scandal\"], [[Associated Press]]/[[KOVR]], October 6, 2014</ref> The following October, the tutor was arrested on charges of burglary, computer access and fraud.<ref name=\"CBSLA\" /><ref name=\"CBSLA\" /><ref name=\"DP\" /><ref name=\"KPCC\" /><ref name=\"MyNewsLa\" /><ref>[https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2014/10/high-school-tutor-accused-of-planning-keylogging-ring-finally-arrested/ \"High school tutor accused of planning keylogging ring finally arrested\"], by [https://arstechnica.com/author/cyrus-farivar/ Cyrus Farivar], [[Ars Technica]], October 7, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/calif-tutor-hacks-teachers-computers-grades-cops-article-1.1966119 \"California high school tutor hacked into teachers' computers, changed grades \u2014 then fled the country: cops\"], by [http://www.nydailynews.com/authors?author=Meg-Wagner Meg Wagner], ''[[New York Daily News]]'', October 7, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Tutor-Arrested-in-Grade-Changing-Scheme-278398991.html \"Tutor Arrested in Grade-Changing Scheme\"] by Kelly Goff, [[City News Service]]/[[KNBC]], October 7, 2014.</ref> In response to the hacking and \"prom draft\" scandals, the school hired an \"ethics consultant\" in June 2014, with hopes of restoring the school's reputation.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/jun/13/ethics-expert-hired-after-high-school-scandals/ \"Ethics expert hired after high school scandals\"], [[Associated Press]]/[[The Washington Times]], June 13, 2014</ref>  The consultant's duties include training the students to accept diversity and be more honest and inclusive.<ref name=\"7signs\">[http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2014/05/corona_del_mar_high_school_pro.php \"7 Signs Corona del Mar High School May Be the Incubator of Orange County's Evils\"] by Matt Coker, ''[[OC Weekly]]'', May 13, 2014</ref><ref name=lat20140507>{{cite news|last=Flores|first=Adolfo|title='Prom draft' reflects Newport Beach culture, ex-school official says|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-cdm-prom-draft-culture-20140507-story.html|accessdate=May 16, 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dailypilot.com/news/tn-dpt-me-0611-ethics-consultant-20140610,0,3568849.story \"District hires ethics consultant in wake of cheating scandal\"], by Hannah Fry, ''[[Daily Pilot]]'', June 10, 2014</ref><ref name=hacking>{{cite news|last=Steussy|first=Lauren|title=11 students removed from Corona del Mar High in hacking case|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/students-599284-school-accused.html?page=2|accessdate=May 29, 2014|newspaper=The Orange County Register|date=January 28, 2014|author2=Petersen, Melody|author3=Cooley, Ryah}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nThe school has been placed on multiple national and state-level lists of \"top schools\". In 2011 ''[[U.S. News and World Report]]'' ranked it 127 of 21,786 high schools in math and science<ref>{{cite web|title=Best High Schools: Gold and Silver Medal Schools by the Numbers|url=http://education.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-high-schools/rankings/math-science?page=6|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=December 18, 2011|year=2011}}</ref> and ''[[Newsweek]]'' included it as number 172 of the 500 best high schools in the United States.<ref name =newsweektop500>{{cite web|title=America's Best High Schools|url=http://www.newsweek.com/newsweeks-annual-list-best-high-schools-america-67863|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|publisher=[[The Newsweek Daily Beast Company]]|accessdate=December 17, 2011|date=June 19, 2011}}</ref> It earned a gold medal from ''U.S. News and World Report'' in 2014, with a national ranking of 222 (37 in California).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/newport-mesa-unified-school-district/corona-del-mar-high-school-2887|title=Corona del Mar High School in NEWPORT BEACH, CA - Best High Schools - US News|work=usnews.com}}</ref> [[Niche.com]] ranked the school #255 out of 19,112 Best College Prep Public High Schools in America in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/corona-del-mar-high-school-newport-beach-ca/rankings/|title=2020 Corona Del Mar High School Rankings|website=Niche|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nCorona del Mar competes in the Sunset Conference of the [[CIF Southern Section]], having moved from the Pacific Coast League following<ref>Turner, Andrew. \u201cNew Sunset League Gets Some Things Right, but Not All Are in Agreement.\u201d Los Angeles Times, Los Angeles Times, 3 Mar. 2018, www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/sports/tn-dpt-sp-sunset-league-surf-wave-fall-20180303-story.html.</ref> the 2017\u20132018 season. The Sea Kings have won 81 CIF Southern Section Championships and 12 [[California Interscholastic Federation]] State Championships.\n\nThe school opened a $1.75 million aquatic center in 1992.<ref name=\"OCM92\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4xEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=%22Corona+del+Mar+High+School%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=q_U9VIirO4P5yATp44H4Ag&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBjgU#v=onepage&q=%241.75&f=false|title=Water Polo: Going for the Gold|last=E.B.|date=Feb 1992|work=Orange Coast Magazine|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> An evening fundraiser in 2007 raised $221,000 for a refurbishment project.<ref name=\"OCM2007\">{{cite book|last=Gloria Zigner|first=|title=Orange Coast Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wQYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA44|accessdate=October 15, 2014|date=July 2007|publisher=Emmis Communications|pages=44\u2013|chapter=Zignature}}</ref> They have won the Boys' [[Water polo]] southern section divisional title 13 times,<ref>{{cite web|title=CIF Southern Section All Sports Press Guide and Record Book|url=http://www.cifss.org/pdfs/record_book_new.pdf|publisher=CIF|pages=307\u2013310|accessdate=December 22, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69eubbr8I?url=http://www.cifss.org/pdfs/record_book_new.pdf|archivedate=August 4, 2012}}</ref> including nine Division 1 titles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Albano|first=Dan|title=Boys' water polo: Corona del Mar-Long Beach Wilson CIF final preview/poll|url=http://ocvarsity.freedomblogging.com/2011/11/18/boys-water-polo-corona-del-mar-long-beach-wilson-cif-final-preview/241743/|accessdate=December 25, 2011|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe school has won six State Championships in Girls' [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]. In 2010 the boys' soccer team won the SoCal State Championship and finished ranked second in the nation. In 2011 the boys' volleyball team won the Powerade Fab 50 ESPN Rise National championship trophy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Calhoun|first=Damian|title=ESPN award caps CdM's storybook season|url=http://www.ocvarsity.com/articles/team-27142-cif-title.html|accessdate=December 14, 2011|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> The high school also competes in sailing, crew and surfing. Corona del Mar Football won the [[List of California state high school football champions|Division III State Football Championship]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/8TBW_CEwEEyeIYoRE17EZA/2013-maxpreps-california-division-iii-all-state-football-teams.htm|title=2013 MaxPreps California Division III All-State Football Teams|date=January 31, 2014|first=Kevin|last=Askeland|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nParent and booster groups annually raise large sums of money for the school and related extracurricular programs, with just three of the projects raising a total of over $235,000 annually.<ref name=\"PerrucciPerrucci2009\">{{cite book|last1=Perrucci|first1=Robert|last2=Perrucci|first2=Carolyn C.|title=America at Risk: The Crisis of Hope, Trust, and Caring|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajJC8kU8I54C&pg=PA44|accessdate=October 15, 2014|date=June 15, 2009 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780742566323|pages=44\u2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CDM high school photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|CDM high school]]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Tumua Anae]], Olympic water polo goalie<ref>{{cite news| title =Tumua Anae Profile| url =http://www.usctrojans.com/sports/w-wpolo/mtt/anae_tumua01.html| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120826055828/http://www.usctrojans.com/sports/w-wpolo/mtt/anae_tumua01.html| archivedate =2012-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Debbie Cook]], 2007-2008 mayor of [[Huntington Beach, California]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Segura |first=Joe |title=Huntington Beach Mayor Debbie Cook, a Congress hopeful, knows how to hold her ground |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]] |accessdate=September 12, 2008 |url=http://www2.presstelegram.com/news/ci_10451559 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926010143/http://www2.presstelegram.com/news/ci_10451559 |archivedate=September 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n*[[Taylor Dent]], tennis player<ref>{{cite news|title=Agassi advances but he won't face Dent |url=http://www.ocregister.com/ocr/sections/sports/other/article_630698.php |work=Orange County Register |date=August 11, 2005 |accessdate=September 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007170842/http://www.ocregister.com/ocr/sections/sports/other/article_630698.php |archivedate=October 7, 2008 }}</ref>\n*[[Firoozeh Dumas]], author\n*[[Kevin Hansen (volleyball)|Kevin Hansen]], Olympic indoor volleyball player<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Hansen helps Team USA to Olympic win |url=http://www.dailypilot.com/articles/2008/08/23/sports/cdm/dpt-spolympics081608.txt |work=Daily Pilot|publisher= |date= | accessdate = December 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n* [[John Ireland (sportscaster)|John Ireland]], sportscaster<ref name=\"Virgen\">{{cite news|last=Virgen|first=Steve|title=CdM alums excited for gig|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/tn-dpt-1224-spvirgen-20111223,0,5073897,full.story|accessdate=February 19, 2012|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=December 24, 2011}}</ref> \n*[[Matt Keough]], baseball player<ref>{{cite web | title = Matt Keough | work = www.thebaseballcube.com  | url = http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/K/matt-keough.shtml }}</ref>\n*[[William Leach (canoeist)|Bill Leach]], Olympic canoer<ref>{{cite news|last=Weyler|first=John|title=There's Always Another Option: No Matter What the Obstacle, Leach Finds a Way to Compete|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-05-23/sports/sp-3440_1_bill-leach| accessdate = December 18, 2011 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 23, 1991}}</ref>\n*[[Julie Leach]], Olympic canoer, triathlete<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/le/julie-leach-1.html|title=Julie Leach|work=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> \n*[[Brad Alan Lewis]], Olympic gold medalist in rowing<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunn|first=Richard|title=Hall of Fame: Brad Lewis (Corona del Mar)|url=http://articles.dailypilot.com/2002-05-13/news/export36862_1_rowing-corona-del-mar-bob-ernst| accessdate = December 18, 2011 |newspaper=[[Daily Pilot]]|date=May 13, 2002}}</ref>\n*[[Bill Macdonald]], sportscaster<ref name=\"Virgen\"/> \n*[[Eric Marienthal]], Jazz Musician<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=He's got it covered |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/marienthal-70431-record-very.html |work=www.ocregister.com |publisher= |date= | accessdate = July 26, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Jack McBean]], soccer player<ref>{{cite news | last = French | first = Scott  | title = GALAXY: McBean prepares for next step  | work = [[ESPN]] | date = December 14, 2011  | url = http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/12944/galaxy-teen-mcbean-prepares-for-next-step| accessdate = January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Mark McGrath]], lead singer of the pop rock band [[Sugar Ray]]\n*[[McG]], film director and producer<ref>{{cite news| last = Koltnow| first = Barry | title = Who wants to mess with 'Terminator'?  | work = [[Orange County Register]] | date = May 20, 2009  | url = http://www.ocregister.com/articles/movie-mcg-told-2419948-terminator-people | accessdate = December 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[John Mann (water polo)|John Mann]], Olympic water polo player<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=John Mann Bio|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/water-polo/john-mann-bio.html}}</ref>\n*[[Leslie Mann]], actress<ref>{{cite news | last = Koltnow | first = Barry  | title = What Leslie Mann Misses Most About O.C.  | work = [[Orange County Register]] | date = December 19, 2012  | url = http://www.ocregister.com/articles/county-381134-orange-life.html  | accessdate = January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Sam Mikulak]], Olympic gymnast<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-gym/mtt/mikulak_sam00.html|title=Sam Mikulak Bio|work=mgoblue.com}}</ref>\n*[[Madeline Musselman]], 2016 Olympic gold medalist in water polo<ref>{{cite web|url=https://highschool.latimes.com/corona-del-mar-high-school/golden-girl-maddie-musselmans-road-to-rio/|title=Golden Girl: Maddie Musselman\u2019s road to Rio}}</ref>\n*[[Keri Phebus]], tennis player, [[NCAA Women's Tennis Championship|NCAA singles champion]] for [[UCLA]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szabo|first1=Matt|title=Phebus Olson returns to court|url=http://www.latimes.com/tn-dpt-0120-phebus-tennis-20130119-story.html|accessdate=1 September 2017|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=January 19, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Dave Rohde]], baseball player ([[Houston Astros]], [[Cleveland Indians]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Dave Rohde Baseball Stats|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=rohdeda01|website=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=October 9, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Alison Rosen]], podcaster, writer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alisonrosen.com/2014/04/ariynbf-274-speaking-of-speaking-fomo-fit-with-a-kissable-face/ |title=ARIYNBF 274: Speaking of Speaking, FOMO, Fit with a Kissable Face |date=April 30, 2014 |last=Rosen |first=Alison |accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Kelly Rutherford]], actress<ref>{{cite news | title = Gossip Girl Transformations | work = InStyle | url = http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0,,20208061_20207867_20473224,00.html | accessdate = December 18, 2011}}</ref>\n*[[Rodney Sheppard]], guitarist, bass player from pop rock band [[Sugar Ray]]{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n*[[Brad Sherman]], Congressman<ref>{{cite news|last=Feldman|first=Paul|title=CAMPAIGN JOURNAL : Tax Board Duel Fought With Gadgets|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-19/news/mn-2752_1_tax-appeals-board|accessdate=December 18, 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 19, 1990}}</ref> \n*[[Michael Steele (musician)|Michael Steele]], bass guitarist for rock band [[The Bangles]]<ref>{{cite news|title =Corona del Mar High | work =[[Los Angeles Times]]| date =June 9, 1999| url =http://articles.latimes.com/1999/jun/09/news/ss-45847| accessdate = December 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[Jeff Thomason]], football player<ref>{{cite news | last = Springer | first = Steve  | title = Working Vacation in Florida  | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = January 26, 2005  | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jan/26/sports/sp-eagles26  | accessdate = December 18, 2011}}</ref>\n*[[Brian Tyler (composer)|Brian Tyler]], composer, conductor, and producer<ref>{{cite news|title=Talk about entertaining...|url=http://articles.dailypilot.com/2001-12-29/news/export41588_1_newport-beach-tan-dun-orange-coast|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=Daily Pilot|date=December 29, 2001}}</ref>\n*[[Lars Ulrich]], drummer, Metallica<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-20/entertainment/ca-10839_1_heavy-metal-band |title=Drumming Into Metallica |last=Boehm |first=Mike |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 20, 1996 |accessdate=March 5, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[John Vallely]], UCLA and NBA basketball player \n*[[Neil Weber]], baseball player ([[Arizona Diamondbacks]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Neil Weber|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?P=Neil-Weber|work=The Baseball Cube|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n*[[Vanness Wu]], [[Taiwanese American]] pop star<ref>{{cite web|title=Neil Weber|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=corona+del+mar+high+school+vanness+wu&sxsrf=ALeKk03O8Hj1AhS1hkYATj3Xr-7tjFJdUA:1587502100335&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjq1pSWsvroAhWNvZ4KHQ6WACwQ_AUoAnoECAwQBA&biw=1280&bih=721#imgrc=NRjN3pimsNrRuM|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://cdm.nmusd.us/}}\n*[http://www.nmusd.k12.ca.us/ Newport Mesa Unified School District]\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1962]]\n[[Category:High schools in Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n[[Category:Public middle schools in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name              =Corona del Mar High School \n|image             =CDM high school front entrance photo D Ramey Logan.jpg\n|caption           = Corona del Mar High School Front Entrance: April 2015\n|streetaddress     =2101 Eastbluff Drive \n|city              =[[Newport Beach, California|Newport Beach]] \n|state             =[[California]] \n|zipcode           =92660\n|coordinates       ={{Coord|33.633537|-117.876686|type:edu_region:US-CA|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|district          =[[Newport-Mesa Unified School District]]\n|principal         =Kathy Scott (9-12), Becky Gogel (7-8)   \n|type              =[[Public school (government funded)|Public]] \n|grades            = 7 - 12 \n|motto             = Cultivate Integrity, Develop Resiliency, Model Empathy\n|team_name         = Sea Kings, Sea Queens (high school)<br> Riptide (junior high school)\n|nickname          = Home of the Sea Kings\n|conference = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[CIF Southern Section|Southern Section]] <br/> [[Sunset League (California)|Sunset League]]\n|rival             = [[Newport Harbor High School|Newport Harbor]]\n|colors            = Navy, Columbia blue, Silver, White\n|established       = 1962 \n|ratio             = 25.61<ref name=NCES/>\n|teaching_staff    = 101.20 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|enrollment        = 2,592 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0627240&ID=062724004109|title=Corona del Mar High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|homepage          ={{URL|http://cdm.nmusd.us/}}\n}}\n\n'''Corona del Mar High School''' ('''CdM''') is a public school located in the Eastbluff neighborhood of [[Newport Beach, California]], and belongs to the [[Newport-Mesa Unified School District]].  It is a combination of a middle school (7th and 8th grades) and a high school (9th, 10th, 11th, and 12th grades). The school was founded in 1962 and has an enrollment of just over 2600 students. The school covers an area of just over 1,700,000 square feet. According to US News, there are 92 full-time teachers.\n\nIt has been ranked by ''[[Newsweek]]'' as one of the top 200 high schools in the United States,<ref name =newsweektop500/> and it has been a state champion in several sports. However, it has also been featured in the national media for scandals involving [[homophobia]], [[sexism]], and academic dishonesty.\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Corona Del Mar Middle School photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|The Corona Del Mar Middle School]]\nThe school was founded in 1962. In the mid 1970s, the school went through an extensive design process to develop its media center.<ref name=\"HanniganEstes1978\">{{cite book|last1=Hannigan|first1=Jane Anne|last2=Estes|first2=Glenn E.|title=Media Center Facilities Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAqfAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=October 15, 2014|year=1978|publisher=American Library Association|isbn=9780838932124}}</ref> The Marian Bergeson Aquatic Center, named for state senator [[Marian Bergeson]] who was from Newport Beach, opened in May 1990 at a cost of $1.75 million.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Belson|first1=Eve|title=Water Polo: Going for the Gold|journal=Orange Coast|date=February 1992|page=14 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4xEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=%22corona+del+mar+high+school%22+1990&source=bl&ots=_05sX_WvZt&sig=JA0UjRyfZRcqjC24HyebvZ7iNkU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=w80cVaGDNITnoATs_4FY&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22corona%20del%20mar%20high%20school%22%201990&f=false|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> In March 2015, a {{convert|29,000|sqft|adj=on}} performing arts center was finished. The center cost $16 million and seats more than 360 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corona del Mar High School Unveils New Theater at Ribbon-Cutting Ceremony|url=http://www.coronadelmartoday.com/48511/home/corona-del-mar-high-school-unveils-new-theater-at-ribbon-cutting-ceremony/|website=Corona del Mar Today|accessdate=April 1, 2015|date=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907201559/http://www.coronadelmartoday.com/48511/home/corona-del-mar-high-school-unveils-new-theater-at-ribbon-cutting-ceremony/|archive-date=September 7, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nicolai|first1=Megan|title=Corona del Mar schools unveil $16 million performing arts center|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/school-654134-arts-high.html|work=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=March 13, 2015|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2009 and 2014 Corona del Mar was the subject of a series of controversies concerning [[sexism]] and [[homophobia]]. In February 2009, when a production of the musical [[Rent (musical)|''Rent'']] was cancelled, the theater teacher alleged it was due to the principal objecting to the play's depiction of homosexuality.<ref>[http://www.ocregister.com/articles/school-111922-gay-asrani.html \"Instructor: Play canceled because of gay characters\"], by Jeff Overley, [[Orange County Register]], February 13, 2009</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Rent\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/20/theater/20rent.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1320105752-tii0ffIkGckeG7XOoNOY4Q \"Tamer 'Rent' Is Too Wild for Some Schools\"], by Patrick Healy, ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 19, 2009</ref><ref name=\"Advocate\">[http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/02/27/canceled-high-school-production-rent-back \"Canceled High School Production of Rent Back On\"], by Ross von Metzke, ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', February 27, 2009</ref>  Student demand eventually brought back the play.<ref name=\"Advocate\" /> The following month, after a video surfaced of male students threatening to rape and kill a female peer, the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] sued the school for inadequately responding to, allowing, and even condoning an atmosphere of sexist and homophobic violence.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/19/local/me-aclu-school-suit19 \"ACLU sues Corona del Mar High School for cultivating 'homophobic' environment\"], by Susannah Rosenblatt, [[Los Angeles Times]], March 19, 2009</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/19/theater/19arts-ACLUSUESSCHO_BRF.html?_r=1 \"A.C.L.U. Sues School Involved in 'Rent' Tussle\"], by Patrick Healy, ''The New York Times'', March 18, 2009</ref> A [[settlement (litigation)|settlement]] was reached in September, when the District agreed to create and enforce anti-harassment policies and train both students and staff.<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/settlement-reached-in-california-high-school-rent-case/?hp \"Settlement Reached in California High School 'Rent' Case\"], by Patricia Cohen, ArtsBeat for ''The New York Times'', September 10, 2009</ref> In May 2014, the school again attracted negative attention for an [[National Football League draft|NFL-style]] \"prom draft\" in which female students were ceremonially \"drafted\" as dates by their male peers.<ref>[http://www.ocregister.com/articles/draft-612766-prom-school.html \"High school boys hold 'draft' to pick prom dates\"], by Lauren Steussy, ''[[Orange County Register]]'', May 5, 2014</ref><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/05/calif-high-school-students-accused-of-using-a-prom-draft-to-find-date/ \"Calif. High School Students Accused of Using a 'Prom Draft' to Find Date\"] by Tina Chen, [[American Broadcasting Company]], May 7, 2014</ref> Writers for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' cited a former Corona del Mar High School disciplinarian in their argument that the \"draft\" was the result of a problematic sense of entitlement among Newport Beach residents.<ref name=\"LATimes1\">[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-cdm-prom-draft-culture-20140507-story.html \"'Prom draft' reflects Newport Beach culture, ex-school official says\"] by Adolfo Flores, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', May 7, 2014</ref><ref name=\"LATimes2\">[http://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-0509-prom-draft-20140509-story.html \"School prom 'draft' prompts reflection in exclusive Newport Beach\"] by Adolfo Flores, [[Christopher Goffard]] and Hannah Fry, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', May 8, 2014</ref>\n\nThe school also experienced a series of publicized academic integrity incidents. In 2012, school officials discovered that ten students had bought the answers to their tests from [[Amazon.com]].<ref name=\"7signs\" /><ref>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2012/01/06/corona-del-mar-students-buy-test-banks-off-amazon-com/ \"Corona Del Mar Students Buy Test Banks Off Amazon.com\"], [[CBS]]-LA, January 6, 2012</ref> In early 2014, eleven Corona del Mar High School students were expelled<ref name=\"LATimes2\" /><ref>[http://abc7.com/archive/9411848/ \"Corona del Mar High School hacking: 11 students expelled\"], [[KABC-TV]], January 29, 2014</ref><ref name=\"CBSLA\">[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2014/11/04/tutor-pleads-not-guilty-in-newport-beach-school-hacker-scandal/ \"Tutor Pleads Not Guilty In O.C. School Hacker Scandal\"], [[CBS]]-LA, November 4, 2014</ref><ref name=\"DP\">[http://www.dailypilot.com/news/tn-dpt-me-1006-cdm-arrest-20141006,0,4452919.story \"Police arrest tutor in Corona del Mar High cheating scandal\"], by Hannah Fry, [[Daily Pilot]], October 6, 2014</ref><ref name=KPCC>[http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/10/07/47219/tutor-charged-in-corona-del-mar-high-school-grade/ \"Tutor charged in Corona del Mar High School grade scandal\"], [[Associated Press]]/[[KPCC]], October 7, 2014</ref><ref name=\"MyNewsLa\">[http://mynewsla.com/education/2014/10/07/tutor-alleged-corona-del-mar-cheating-scandal-arrested-lax/ \"Tutor in Alleged Corona Del Mar Cheating Scandal Arrested at LAX\"], by John Schreiber, [http://mynewsla.com/ My News LA], October 7, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.ocregister.com/articles/students-599284-school-accused.html?page=1 \"11 students removed from Corona del Mar High in hacking case\"], by Lauren Steussy, Melody Petersen, and Ryah Cooley, ''[[Orange County Register]]'', January 29, 2014</ref> for hacking into school computers with the help of a tutor to alter their grades.<ref>[http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2014/10/06/orange-county-tutor-charged-in-grade-scandal/ \"Orange County Tutor Charged In Grade Scandal\"], [[Associated Press]]/[[KOVR]], October 6, 2014</ref> The following October, the tutor was arrested on charges of burglary, computer access and fraud.<ref name=\"CBSLA\" /><ref name=\"CBSLA\" /><ref name=\"DP\" /><ref name=\"KPCC\" /><ref name=\"MyNewsLa\" /><ref>[https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2014/10/high-school-tutor-accused-of-planning-keylogging-ring-finally-arrested/ \"High school tutor accused of planning keylogging ring finally arrested\"], by [https://arstechnica.com/author/cyrus-farivar/ Cyrus Farivar], [[Ars Technica]], October 7, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/calif-tutor-hacks-teachers-computers-grades-cops-article-1.1966119 \"California high school tutor hacked into teachers' computers, changed grades \u2014 then fled the country: cops\"], by [http://www.nydailynews.com/authors?author=Meg-Wagner Meg Wagner], ''[[New York Daily News]]'', October 7, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Tutor-Arrested-in-Grade-Changing-Scheme-278398991.html \"Tutor Arrested in Grade-Changing Scheme\"] by Kelly Goff, [[City News Service]]/[[KNBC]], October 7, 2014.</ref> In response to the hacking and \"prom draft\" scandals, the school hired an \"ethics consultant\" in June 2014, with hopes of restoring the school's reputation.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/jun/13/ethics-expert-hired-after-high-school-scandals/ \"Ethics expert hired after high school scandals\"], [[Associated Press]]/[[The Washington Times]], June 13, 2014</ref>  The consultant's duties include training the students to accept diversity and be more honest and inclusive.<ref name=\"7signs\">[http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2014/05/corona_del_mar_high_school_pro.php \"7 Signs Corona del Mar High School May Be the Incubator of Orange County's Evils\"] by Matt Coker, ''[[OC Weekly]]'', May 13, 2014</ref><ref name=lat20140507>{{cite news|last=Flores|first=Adolfo|title='Prom draft' reflects Newport Beach culture, ex-school official says|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-cdm-prom-draft-culture-20140507-story.html|accessdate=May 16, 2014|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dailypilot.com/news/tn-dpt-me-0611-ethics-consultant-20140610,0,3568849.story \"District hires ethics consultant in wake of cheating scandal\"], by Hannah Fry, ''[[Daily Pilot]]'', June 10, 2014</ref><ref name=hacking>{{cite news|last=Steussy|first=Lauren|title=11 students removed from Corona del Mar High in hacking case|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/students-599284-school-accused.html?page=2|accessdate=May 29, 2014|newspaper=The Orange County Register|date=January 28, 2014|author2=Petersen, Melody|author3=Cooley, Ryah}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nThe school has been placed on multiple national and state-level lists of \"top schools\". In 2011 ''[[U.S. News and World Report]]'' ranked it 127 of 21,786 high schools in math and science<ref>{{cite web|title=Best High Schools: Gold and Silver Medal Schools by the Numbers|url=http://education.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-high-schools/rankings/math-science?page=6|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=December 18, 2011|year=2011}}</ref> and ''[[Newsweek]]'' included it as number 172 of the 500 best high schools in the United States.<ref name =newsweektop500>{{cite web|title=America's Best High Schools|url=http://www.newsweek.com/newsweeks-annual-list-best-high-schools-america-67863|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|publisher=[[The Newsweek Daily Beast Company]]|accessdate=December 17, 2011|date=June 19, 2011}}</ref> It earned a gold medal from ''U.S. News and World Report'' in 2014, with a national ranking of 222 (37 in California).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/newport-mesa-unified-school-district/corona-del-mar-high-school-2887|title=Corona del Mar High School in NEWPORT BEACH, CA - Best High Schools - US News|work=usnews.com}}</ref> [[Niche.com]] ranked the school #255 out of 19,112 Best College Prep Public High Schools in America in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/corona-del-mar-high-school-newport-beach-ca/rankings/|title=2020 Corona Del Mar High School Rankings|website=Niche|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nCorona del Mar competes in the Sunset Conference of the [[CIF Southern Section]], having moved from the Pacific Coast League following<ref>Turner, Andrew. \u201cNew Sunset League Gets Some Things Right, but Not All Are in Agreement.\u201d Los Angeles Times, Los Angeles Times, 3 Mar. 2018, www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/sports/tn-dpt-sp-sunset-league-surf-wave-fall-20180303-story.html.</ref> the 2017\u20132018 season. The Sea Kings have won 81 CIF Southern Section Championships and 12 [[California Interscholastic Federation]] State Championships.\n\nThe school opened a $1.75 million aquatic center in 1992.<ref name=\"OCM92\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4xEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=%22Corona+del+Mar+High+School%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=q_U9VIirO4P5yATp44H4Ag&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBjgU#v=onepage&q=%241.75&f=false|title=Water Polo: Going for the Gold|last=E.B.|date=Feb 1992|work=Orange Coast Magazine|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> An evening fundraiser in 2007 raised $221,000 for a refurbishment project.<ref name=\"OCM2007\">{{cite book|last=Gloria Zigner|first=|title=Orange Coast Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wQYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA44|accessdate=October 15, 2014|date=July 2007|publisher=Emmis Communications|pages=44\u2013|chapter=Zignature}}</ref> They have won the Boys' [[Water polo]] southern section divisional title 13 times,<ref>{{cite web|title=CIF Southern Section All Sports Press Guide and Record Book|url=http://www.cifss.org/pdfs/record_book_new.pdf|publisher=CIF|pages=307\u2013310|accessdate=December 22, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69eubbr8I?url=http://www.cifss.org/pdfs/record_book_new.pdf|archivedate=August 4, 2012}}</ref> including nine Division 1 titles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Albano|first=Dan|title=Boys' water polo: Corona del Mar-Long Beach Wilson CIF final preview/poll|url=http://ocvarsity.freedomblogging.com/2011/11/18/boys-water-polo-corona-del-mar-long-beach-wilson-cif-final-preview/241743/|accessdate=December 25, 2011|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe school has won six State Championships in Girls' [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]. In 2010 the boys' soccer team won the SoCal State Championship and finished ranked second in the nation. In 2011 the boys' volleyball team won the Powerade Fab 50 ESPN Rise National championship trophy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Calhoun|first=Damian|title=ESPN award caps CdM's storybook season|url=http://www.ocvarsity.com/articles/team-27142-cif-title.html|accessdate=December 14, 2011|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> The high school also competes in sailing, crew and surfing. Corona del Mar Football won the [[List of California state high school football champions|Division III State Football Championship]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/8TBW_CEwEEyeIYoRE17EZA/2013-maxpreps-california-division-iii-all-state-football-teams.htm|title=2013 MaxPreps California Division III All-State Football Teams|date=January 31, 2014|first=Kevin|last=Askeland|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nParent and booster groups annually raise large sums of money for the school and related extracurricular programs, with just three of the projects raising a total of over $235,000 annually.<ref name=\"PerrucciPerrucci2009\">{{cite book|last1=Perrucci|first1=Robert|last2=Perrucci|first2=Carolyn C.|title=America at Risk: The Crisis of Hope, Trust, and Caring|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajJC8kU8I54C&pg=PA44|accessdate=October 15, 2014|date=June 15, 2009 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780742566323|pages=44\u2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CDM high school photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|CDM high school]]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Tumua Anae]], Olympic water polo goalie<ref>{{cite news| title =Tumua Anae Profile| url =http://www.usctrojans.com/sports/w-wpolo/mtt/anae_tumua01.html| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120826055828/http://www.usctrojans.com/sports/w-wpolo/mtt/anae_tumua01.html| archivedate =2012-08-26}}</ref>\n*[[Debbie Cook]], 2007-2008 mayor of [[Huntington Beach, California]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Segura |first=Joe |title=Huntington Beach Mayor Debbie Cook, a Congress hopeful, knows how to hold her ground |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]] |accessdate=September 12, 2008 |url=http://www2.presstelegram.com/news/ci_10451559 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926010143/http://www2.presstelegram.com/news/ci_10451559 |archivedate=September 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n*[[Taylor Dent]], tennis player<ref>{{cite news|title=Agassi advances but he won't face Dent |url=http://www.ocregister.com/ocr/sections/sports/other/article_630698.php |work=Orange County Register |date=August 11, 2005 |accessdate=September 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007170842/http://www.ocregister.com/ocr/sections/sports/other/article_630698.php |archivedate=October 7, 2008 }}</ref>\n*[[Firoozeh Dumas]], author\n*[[Kevin Hansen (volleyball)|Kevin Hansen]], Olympic indoor volleyball player<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Hansen helps Team USA to Olympic win |url=http://www.dailypilot.com/articles/2008/08/23/sports/cdm/dpt-spolympics081608.txt |work=Daily Pilot|publisher= |date= | accessdate = December 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n* [[John Ireland (sportscaster)|John Ireland]], sportscaster<ref name=\"Virgen\">{{cite news|last=Virgen|first=Steve|title=CdM alums excited for gig|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/tn-dpt-1224-spvirgen-20111223,0,5073897,full.story|accessdate=February 19, 2012|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=December 24, 2011}}</ref> \n*[[Matt Keough]], baseball player<ref>{{cite web | title = Matt Keough | work = www.thebaseballcube.com  | url = http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/K/matt-keough.shtml }}</ref>\n*[[William Leach (canoeist)|Bill Leach]], Olympic canoer<ref>{{cite news|last=Weyler|first=John|title=There's Always Another Option: No Matter What the Obstacle, Leach Finds a Way to Compete|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-05-23/sports/sp-3440_1_bill-leach| accessdate = December 18, 2011 