ia Claghorn\n|\n|-\n|1948\n|data-sort-value=\"Bride Goes Wild, The\"|''[[The Bride Goes Wild]]''\n|Miss Doberly\n|\n|-\n|1948\n|''[[The Man from Texas (1948 film)|The Man from Texas]]''\n|Widow Weeks\n|\n|-\n|1950\n|''[[Kill the Umpire]]''\n|Betty Johnson\n|\n|-\n|1950\n|''[[My Blue Heaven (1950 film)|My Blue Heaven]]''\n|Miss Irma Gilbert\n|\n|-\n|1950\n|''[[Emergency Wedding]]''\n|Emma\n|\n|-\n|1951\n|''[[Rich, Young and Pretty]]''\n|Glynnie\n|\n|-\n|1951\n|data-sort-value=\"Millionaire for Christy, A\"|''[[A Millionaire for Christy]]''\n|Patsy Clifford\n|\n|-\n|1951\n|''[[Golden Girl (1951 film)|Golden Girl]]''\n|Mary Ann Crabtree\n|\n|-\n|1952\n|''[[With a Song in My Heart (film)|With a Song in My Heart]]''\n|Sister Marie\n|\n|-\n|1952\n|data-sort-value=\"Merry Widow, The\"|''[[The Merry Widow (1952 film)|The Merry Widow]]''\n|Kitty Riley\n|\n|-\n|1953\n|''[[I Love Melvin]]''\n|Mom Schneider\n|\n|-\n|1955\n|data-sort-value=\"Kentuckian, The\"|''[[The Kentuckian (1955 film)|The Kentuckian]]''\n|Sophie Wakefield\n|\n|-\n|1956\n|data-sort-value=\"Kettles in the Ozarks, The\"|''[[The Kettles in the Ozarks]]''\n|Miss Bedelia Baines\n|\n|-\n|1956\n|''[[Bundle of Joy]]''\n|Mrs. Dugan\n|\n|-\n|1957\n|data-sort-value=\"Fuzzy Pink Nightgown, The\"|''[[The Fuzzy Pink Nightgown]]''\n|Bertha\n|\n|-\n|1958\n|data-sort-value=\"Girl Most Likely, The\"|''[[The Girl Most Likely]]''\n|Mother\n|\n|-\n|1959\n|data-sort-value=\"Mating Game, The\"|''[[The Mating Game (film)|The Mating Game]]''\n|Ma Larkin\n|\n|-\n|1961\n|data-sort-value=\"Parent Trap, The\"|''[[The Parent Trap (1961 film)|The Parent Trap]]''\n|Verbena\n|\n|-\n|1961\n|''[[Summer and Smoke (film)|Summer and Smoke]]''\n|Mrs. Winemiller\n|\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[Summer Magic]]''\n|Mariah Popham\n|\n|-\n|1964\n|data-sort-value=\"Tiger Walks, A\"|''[[A Tiger Walks]]''\n|Mrs. Watkins\n|\n|-\n|1966\n|''[[Spinout (film)|Spinout]]''\n|Violet Ranley\n|\n|}\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1952\n|''[[Four Star Playhouse]]''\n|Rose Barton\n|\"My Wife Geraldine\"\n|-\n|1953\n|''[[Schlitz Playhouse of Stars]]''\n|\n|\"Guardian of the Clock\"\n|-\n|1953\n|''[[Your Jeweler's Showcase]]''\n|\n|\"The Monkey's Paw\"\n|-\n|1953\n|''[[Willys Theatre Presenting Ben Hecht's Tales of the City]]''\n|\n|\"Miracle in the Rain\"\n|-\n|1954\n|''[[Westinghouse Studio One]]''\n|Parsis McHugh\n|\"Two Little Minks\"\n|-\n|1955\n|''[[Kraft Television Theatre]]''\n|\n|\"Trucks Welcome\"\n|-\n|1956\n|''Calling Terry Conway''\n|Pearl McGrath\n|TV film\n|-\n|1957\n|''[[Playhouse 90]]''\n|Louise Hoagland\n|\"The Greer Case\"\n|-\n|1957\n|data-sort-value=\"Red Skelton Show, The\"|''[[The Red Skelton Show]]''\n|Mrs. Van Wyck\n|\"Freddie and the Happy Helper\"\n|-\n|1957\n|''[[Climax!]]''\n|Maud\n|\"The Secret of the Red Room\"\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[DuPont Show of the Month]]''\n|Aladdin's Mother\n|\"Cole Porter's 'Aladdin'\"\n|-\n|1958\n|data-sort-value=\"United States Steel Hour, The\"|''[[The United States Steel Hour]]''\n|\n|\"Flint and Fire\"\n|-\n|1962\n|data-sort-value=\"Real McCoys, The\"|''[[The Real McCoys]]''\n|Mrs. Gaylord\n|\"The New Housekeeper\"\n|-\n|1963\n|data-sort-value=\"Bill Dana Show, The\"|''[[The Bill Dana Show]]''\n|Mrs. Hatten\n|\"The Poker Game\"\n|-\n|1963\u20131965\n|''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]''\n|Clara Lovelace / Mrs. Thomas Barrett / Miss Samantha Cartier\n|3 episodes\n|-\n|1964\n|data-sort-value=\"Cara Williams Show, The\"|''The Cara Williams Show''\n|Amelia Hofstetter\n|\"Amelia Hofstetter, Please Go Home\"\n|-\n|1964\n|''[[Destry (TV series)|Destry]]''\n|Granny Farrell\n|\"Law and Order Day\"\n|-\n|1968\n|''[[I Spy (1965 TV series)|I Spy]]''\n|Aunt Alma\n|\"Home to Judgment\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n {{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last= Alistair |first= Rupert |title= The Name Below the Title : 65 Classic Movie Character Actors from Hollywood's Golden Age |chapter= Una Merkel |pages= 172-175 |date= 2018 |edition= First |type= softcover |publisher= Independently published |location= Great Britain |isbn = 978-1-7200-3837-5}}\n* {{cite book |last= Kinder |first= Larry Sean |title= Una Merkel: The Actress With Sassy Wit and Southern Charm |date= 2016 \n|edition= First |type= hardcover |publisher= BearManor Media |location= Albany, GA |isbn = 978-1-59393-902-1}} \n* {{cite book |last= Maltin |first= Leonard |title= The Real Stars : Profiles and Interviews of Hollywood's Unsung Featured Players |chapter= Una Merkel |pages= 187-217 |date= 2015 |edition= Sixth / eBook |orig-year=First published 1969 |type= softcover |publisher= CreateSpace Independent |location= Great Britain |isbn = 978-1-5116-4485-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|0580916}}\n* [http://www.nkyviews.com/kenton/merkel_thumbs.htm Photographs of Covington, Kentucky's Una Merkel]\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=1100 Photographs of Una Merkel]\n* {{Find a Grave|1750}}\n\n{{TonyAward PlayFeaturedActress 1947-1975}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merkel, Una}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Methodists]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American radio actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American United Methodists]]\n[[Category:Burials in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:People from Covington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Una Merkel\n| image         = Una Merkel - still.JPG\n| caption       = Merkel in 1934\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1903|12|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Covington, Kentucky]], U.S. \n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1986|1|2|1903|12|10|mf=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Highland Cemetery, [[Fort Mitchell, Kentucky]]\n| yearsactive   = 1920\u20131968\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Ronald Burla|1932|1947|end=divorced}}\n}}\n\n'''Una Merkel''' (December 10, 1903&nbsp;\u2013 January 2, 1986) was an [[United States|American]] stage, film, radio, and television actress.\n\nMerkel was born in Kentucky and acted on stage in New York in the 1920s. She went to Hollywood in 1930 and became a popular film actress. Two of her best-known performances are in the films ''[[42nd Street (film)|42nd Street]]'' and ''[[Destry Rides Again]]''. She won a [[Tony Award]] in 1956 and was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in 1961.\n\n==Life and career==\nMerkel was born in [[Covington, Kentucky]], to Bessie (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Phares) and Arno Merkel,<ref>Kentucky. Birth Records, 1847-1911</ref>but in her early childhood, she lived in many of the [[Southern United States]] due to her father's job as a traveling salesman. At the age of 15, she and her parents moved to [[Philadelphia]]. They stayed there a year or so before settling in [[New York City]], where she began attending the Alviene School of Dramatic Art.\n\nBecause of her strong resemblance to actress [[Lillian Gish]], Merkel was offered a part as Gish's youngest sister in a silent film called ''World Shadows''. Unfortunately, the public never saw the film because funding for it dried up, and it was never completed. Merkel went on to appear in a few [[silent movies]], several of them for the Lee Bradford Corporation. She also appeared in the two-reel ''[[Love's Old Sweet Song (1923 film)|Love's Old Sweet Song]]'' (1923), which was made by [[Lee DeForest]] in his [[Phonofilm]] [[sound-on-film]] process and starred [[Louis Wolheim]] and Helen Weir. Not making much of a mark in films, Merkel turned her attention to the theater and found work in several important plays on Broadway. Her biggest triumph was in ''Coquette'' (1927), which starred her idol, [[Helen Hayes]].\n\n[[File:42nd-Street-Merkel-Keeler-Rogers.jpg|thumb|Una Merkel, [[Ruby Keeler]] and [[Ginger Rogers]] in ''[[42nd Street (film)|42nd Street]]'' (1933)]]\n[[File:Gary Cooper Phyllis Brooks Una Merkel, Brisbane 1943 (1).jpg|thumb|right|Una Merkel (right) with [[Phyllis Brooks]] and [[Gary Cooper]] at a [[Brisbane]] press conference on their way to entertain the troops (1943)]]\n[[File:Una Merkel in I Love Melvin trailer.jpg|thumb|right|As Mom Schneider in ''[[I Love Melvin]]'' (1953)]]\n\nInvited to Hollywood by famous director [[D.W. Griffith]] to play [[Ann Rutledge]] in his film ''[[Abraham Lincoln (1930 film)|Abraham Lincoln]]'' (1930), Merkel became a big success in sound films. During the 1930s, she became a popular second lead in a number of films, usually playing the wisecracking best friend of the heroine, supporting actresses such as [[Jean Harlow]], [[Carole Lombard]], [[Loretta Young]], and [[Eleanor Powell]].<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news |last=Reid |first=Alexander |title=Una Merket Dies at Age of 82; From Silent Films to a Tony |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 January 1986 |page=24 }}</ref>\n\nWith her Kewpie-doll looks, strong Southern accent, and wry line delivery, Merkel left her mark on scores of films in the 1930s. She played [[Sam Spade]]'s secretary in the original 1931 version of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1931 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]''. Merkel was a [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] contract player from 1932 to 1938, appearing in as many as 12 films in a year, often on loan-out to other studios. She was also often cast as leading lady opposite [[Jack Benny]], [[Harold Lloyd]], [[Franchot Tone]], and [[Charles Butterworth (actor)|Charles Butterworth]], among others.\n\nIn ''[[42nd Street (film)|42nd Street]]'' (1933), Merkel played a streetwise show girl who was [[Ginger Rogers]]' character's buddy. In the famous \"Shuffle Off to Buffalo\" number, Merkel and Rogers sang the verse: \"Matrimony is baloney. She'll be wanting alimony in a year or so./Still they go and shuffle, shuffle off to Buffalo.\" Merkel appeared in both the [[The Merry Widow (1934 film)|1934]] and the [[The Merry Widow (1952 film)|1952]] film versions of ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', playing different roles.\n\nOne of her most famous roles was in the Western comedy ''[[Destry Rides Again]]'' (1939), in which her character, Lily Belle, gets into a famous \"cat-fight\" with Frenchie ([[Marlene Dietrich]]) over the possession of her husband's trousers, won by Frenchie in a crooked card game. She played the elder daughter to the [[W. C. Fields]] character, Egbert Sous\u00e9, in the 1940 film ''[[The Bank Dick]]''. Her film career went into decline during the 1940s, although she continued working in smaller productions. In 1950, she starred with [[William Bendix]] in the baseball comedy ''[[Kill the Umpire]]'', which was a surprise hit.\n\nShe made a comeback as a middle-aged woman playing mothers and maiden aunts, and in 1956 won a [[Tony Award]] for her role on Broadway in ''The Ponder Heart'', adapted from the [[The Ponder Heart|novella of the same name]]. She had a major part in the MGM 1959 film ''[[The Mating Game (film)|The Mating Game]]'' as [[Paul Douglas (actor)|Paul Douglas]]'s character's wife and [[Debbie Reynolds]]' character's mother, and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] in ''[[Summer and Smoke (film)|Summer and Smoke]]'' (1961). She was also featured as [[Brian Keith]]'s character's housekeeper, Verbena, in the [[Walt Disney]] comedy ''[[The Parent Trap (1961 film)|The Parent Trap]]'' in 1961. Her final film role was opposite [[Elvis Presley]] in ''[[Spinout (film)|Spinout]]'' (1966).\n\n==Personal life==\nOn March 5, 1945, Merkel was nearly killed when her mother Bessie, with whom she shared an apartment in New York City, committed suicide by gassing herself. Merkel was overcome by the five gas jets her mother had turned on in their kitchen and was found unconscious in her bedroom.<ref name=\"starnews\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1454&dat=19520304&id=X29gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LXINAAAAIBAJ&pg=3526,445324&hl=en |title=Una Merkel Lies In Coma After Pill Overdose |date=March 4, 1952 |newspaper=Star-News |page=4 |accessdate=March 22, 2015 |location=Wilmington, North Carolina}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19450306&id=5fVeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QFQMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4457,3137762&hl=en |title=Una Merkel in Death Escape |date=March 6, 1945 |newspaper=[[Lodi News-Sentinel]] |page=8 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 1952, seven years almost to the day after her mother committed suicide, Merkel overdosed on sleeping pills.<ref name=\"starnews\"/> She was found unconscious by a nurse who was caring for her at the time and remained in a coma for a day before recovering.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1301&dat=19520306&id=W_NjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5rADAAAAIBAJ&pg=1537,727712&hl=en |title=Una Merkel Recovering |date=March 6, 1952 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |page=3 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMerkel was a lifelong [[Methodist]].<ref>kyumc.org/events/detail/1806</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fumceunice.org/About.html |title=About FUMC |website=First United Methodist Church, Eunice, Louisiana |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115123221/http://www.fumceunice.org/About.html |archivedate=November 15, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Marriage===\nMerkel was married once and had no children.<ref name=\"folkart\">{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1986-01-04/local/me-24219_1_individual-films |title=Una Merkel, Movie, Stage Actress, Dies |last=Folkart |first=Burt A. |date=January 4, 1986 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> She married [[North American Aviation]] executive Ronald L. Burla in 1932.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19461202&id=DMMwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YGoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5398,5223118&hl=en |title=Divorce Is Sought By Una Merkel |date=December 3, 1946 |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |page=2 |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> They separated in April 1944. Merkel filed for divorce on December 19, 1946 in [[Miami]], and it was granted in March 1947.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=Una Merkel Files Suit on Back Alimony |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/381275669/?terms=Una%2BMerkel%2BFiles%2BSuit%2Bon%2BBack%2BAlimony |date=November 6, 1947 |work=Los Angeles Times |page=2 |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn January 2, 1986, Merkel died in Los Angeles at the age of 82.<ref name=\"folkart\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1982&dat=19860105&id=kYZGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VjMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4011,301370&hl=en |title=Actress Una Merkel dies |date=January 5, 1986 |work=The Evening News |page=2A |accessdate=March 22, 2015 |location=Newburgh, New York}}</ref> She is buried near her parents, Arno and Bessie Merkel, in Highland Cemetery in [[Fort Mitchell, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Tenkotte |editor1-first=Paul A. |editor2-last=Claypool |editor2-first=James C. |title=The Encyclopedia of Northern Kentucky |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zc0eBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Encyclopedia+of+Northern+Kentucky&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZ7s_ztNTgAhUDSa0KHXuhChMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Una%20Merkel&f=false |date=January 13, 2015 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=978-0813159966 |page=615}}</ref>\n\nFor her contribution to the motion picture industry, Una Merkel has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] (6230 Hollywood Boulevard).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/una-merkel/ |title=Hollywood Star Walk: Una Merkel |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> In 1991, a historical marker was dedicated to her in her hometown of Covington.\n\n==Filmography==\n:''For TV movies, see the Television credits section.''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1923\n|''[[Love's Old Sweet Song (1923 film)|Love's Old Sweet Song]]''\n|\n|Short\n|-\n|1924\n|data-sort-value=\"Fifth Horseman, The\"|''The Fifth Horseman''\n|Dorothy\n|\n|-\n|1930\n|''[[Abraham Lincoln (1930 film)|Abraham Lincoln]]''\n|[[Ann Rutledge]]\n|\n|-\n|1930\n|data-sort-value=\"Eyes of the World, The\"|''[[The Eyes of the World]]''\n|Sybil\n|\n|-\n|1930\n|data-sort-value=\"Bat Whispers, The\"|''[[The Bat Whispers]]''\n|Dale Van Gorder\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|''[[Command Performance (1931 film)|Command Performance]]''\n|Princess Katerina\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|''[[Don't Bet on Women]]''\n|Tallulah Hope\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|''[[Six Cylinder Love (1931 film)|Six Cylinder Love]]''\n|Margaret Rogers\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|data-sort-value=\"Maltese Falcon, The\"|''[[The Maltese Falcon (1931 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]''\n|Effie Perine\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|''[[Daddy Long Legs (1931 film)|Daddy Long Legs]]''\n|Sally McBride\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|data-sort-value=\"Bargain, The\"|''[[The Bargain (1931 film)|The Bargain]]''\n|Etta\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|''[[Wicked (1931 film)|Wicked]]''\n|June\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|data-sort-value=\"Secret Witness, The\"|''[[The Secret Witness]]''\n|Lois Martin\n|\n|-\n|1931\n|''[[Private Lives (film)|Private Lives]]''\n|Sibyl\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|''[[She Wanted a Millionaire]]''\n|Mary Taylor\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|data-sort-value=\"Impatient Maiden, The\"|''[[The Impatient Maiden]]''\n|Betty Merrick\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|''[[Man Wanted]]''\n|Ruth 'Ruthie' Holman\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|''[[Huddle (film)|Huddle]]''\n|Thelma\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|''[[Red-Headed Woman]]''\n|Sally\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|''[[They Call It Sin]]''\n|Dixie Dare\n|\n|-\n|1932\n|''[[Men Are Such Fools (1932 film)|Men Are Such Fools]]''\n|Molly\n|\n|-\n|1933\n|''[[Whistling in the Dark (1933 film)|Whistling in the Dark]]''\n|Toby Van Buren\n