ia |location= Albany, GA |isbn = 978-1-59393-902-1}} \n* {{cite book |last= Maltin |first= Leonard |title= The Real Stars : Profiles and Interviews of Hollywood's Unsung Featured Players |chapter= Una Merkel |pages= 187-217 |date= 2015 |edition= Sixth / eBook |orig-year=First published 1969 |type= softcover |publisher= CreateSpace Independent |location= Great Britain |isbn = 978-1-5116-4485-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|0580916}}\n* [http://www.nkyviews.com/kenton/merkel_thumbs.htm Photographs of Covington, Kentucky's Una Merkel]\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=1100 Photographs of Una Merkel]\n* {{Find a Grave|1750}}\n\n{{TonyAward PlayFeaturedActress 1947-1975}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merkel, Una}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Methodists]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American radio actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American United Methodists]]\n[[Category:Burials in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:People from Covington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "EoGuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Una_Merkel"}
{"title_page": "Mariko Mori", "text_new": "{{for|the Japanese volleyball player|Mariko Mori (volleyball)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Mariko Mori <br> \u68ee \u4e07\u91cc\u5b50\n| image = Mori Mariko at the Japan Society Panel on Art & Nature 2010.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| caption = Mariko Mori at the Japan Society Panel on Art & Nature on 2010\n| birth_name = \u68ee \u4e07\u91cc\u5b50\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|02|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| nationality = Japanese\n| spouse = \n| field = [[Photography]],  [[Digital art]], [[Sculpture]]\n| movement = Contemporary Art, Pop Art, Environmental Art\n| elected = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| alma_mater = [[Chelsea College of Art and Design]]\n| alt = Mariko Mori\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Mariko Mori'''|\u68ee \u4e07\u91cc\u5b50|Mori Mariko|born 1967}} is a Japanese [[Interdisciplinarity|multidisciplinary]] [[artist]]. She is known for her photographs and videos of her hybridized future self, often presented in various guises and featuring traditional Japanese motifs. Her work often explores themes of technology, spirituality and transcendence. \n\nIn 2010, she founded the [[Faou Foundation]], an art nonprofit based in New York City.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMariko Mori was born in Tokyo, Japan in 1967.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/Magazine/features/itoi/itoi11-20-01.asp|title=artnet.com Magazine Reviews - Tea with Mariko|last=Itoi|first=Kay|date=2001-11-20|website=Artnet.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05|quote=born in 1967, you are from one of the world's wealthiest families but you have never publicly spoken about it.}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/Mariko-Mori|title=Art Collection Online: Mariko Mori|last=|first=|date=|website=The Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artistproject.metmuseum.org/2/mariko-mori/|title=The Artist Project: Mariko Mori on Botticelli's The Annunciation|last=|first=|date=|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-04|quote=Mariko Mori, born in 1967, is a Japanese multidisciplinary artist interested in history and science. She is based in London, New York, and Tokyo.}}</ref> She comes from a wealthy family; her father is an inventor and technician, and her mother is an art historian of European Art.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.widewalls.ch/artist/mariko-mori/|title=Mariko Mori|website=Widewalls|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> \n\nWhile studying at [[Bunka Fashion College]] in Tokyo in the late 1980s, Mori worked as a [[fashion model]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jca-online.com/mori.html|title=Mariko Mori Interview|last=Sugiura|first=Kuni\u00e9|date=|website=www.jca-online.com|publisher=Journal of Contemporary Art, Inc|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05|quote=Mori: That originates from when I was a fashion model, at around age sixteen. Often I designed my own cloths and made them myself (I studied at a fashion college)}}</ref> In 1989, she moved to [[London]] to study at [[Byam Shaw School of Art]] and the [[Chelsea College of Art and Design]], she studied there until she graduated in 1992.<ref>Hallmark, Kara Kelley. 2007. Encyclopedia of Asian American artists. Westport, Conn: Greenwood Press. p. 129.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artandculture.com/artists/mariko-mori/|title=Mariko Mori|website=Art+Culture Projects|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> After graduating, she moved to New York City and participated in the [[Whitney Independent Study Program]] at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-may-27-ca-53666-story.html|title='Nirvana' Via Spectacle|date=1998-05-27|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMori's early work references traditional Japanese culture and ancient history but is characterized by futuristic themes and characters. Her early photography is heavily influenced by [[cosplay]]. Fantastic deities, robots, alien creatures, and spaceships are featured in video and photography with the artist herself dressed up in various self-made costumes as these characters.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Holzwarth|first1=Hans W.|title=100 Contemporary Artists A-Z|date=2009|publisher=Taschen|location=K\u00f6ln|isbn=978-3-8365-1490-3|pages=386\u2013391|edition=Taschen's 25th anniversary special}}</ref>\n\nPresent throughout her career is a fascination with technology and spirituality, with technology as a means of transcending and transforming consciousness and self.\n\nMori's early works, such as photograph ''Play with Me'' (1994), use her own body as the subject, and she costumes herself as a sexualized, technological alien woman in everyday scenes. While her tableaus are fantastic and futuristic, the role played by the female characters she portrayed were often traditional, gendered roles such as a waitress in ''Tea Ceremony'' (1995), a futuristic version of the female Buddhist deity [[Kissh\u014dten|Kichijoten]] in ''Pure Land'' (1996-1998), or a female Japanese pop star in ''Birth of a Star.'' \n\nMori attributes her fascination with consciousness and death to experiencing [[sleep paralysis]] in her early-twenties for several hours which left her unsure if she was alive or dead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kyotojournal.org/the-journal/culture-arts/synthetic-dreams-the-art-of-mariko-mori/|title=The Art of Mariko Mori {{!}} Kyoto Journal|website=www.kyotojournal.org|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe juxtaposition of Eastern mythology with Western culture is a common theme in Mori's works, often through layering photography and digital imaging,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carnegiemuseums.org/cmag/bk_issue/1998/julaug/feat5.htm|title=Mariko Mori and Salvador Dali|last=Wilson|first=Ellen S.|date=July 1998|website=Carnegie Magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618000008/http://www.carnegiemuseums.org/cmag/bk_issue/1998/julaug/feat5.htm|archive-date=2008-06-18|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> such as in her 1995 installation ''Birth of a Star.'' Later works, such as ''Nirvana'' show her as a goddess, transcending her early roles via technology and image, and abandoning realistic urban scenes for more alien landscapes.\n\nAt the [[47th Venice Biennale]] (1997), Mori had two works exhibited at two different places, a photo collage titled, Empty Dream (1995) shown in the Japanese Pavillon, and the 3-D video installation, Nirvana (1997) which was shown in the Nordic Pavillon.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hz-journal.org/n4/borggreen.html|title=Hz #4 - Japan in Scandinavia|last=Borggreen|first=Gunhild|date=|website=www.hz-journal.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\nMori's work is featured in many public museum collections, including [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]],<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (LACMA),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/211751|title=Esoteric Cosmos|last=|first=|date=|website=LACMA Collections|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcachicago.org/Collection/Items/1995/Mariko-Mori-Birth-Of-A-Star-1995|title=Mariko Mori, Birth of a Star, 1995|website=MCA|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> and others.\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is married to composer Ken Ikeda.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/11/arts/design/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori-at-japan-society.html|title=A Turnabout From Manga to Zen|last=Rosenberg|first=Karen|date=2013-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> They have created collaborative work together, with Ikeda composing music and/or sound for many of Mori's pieces.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Work ==\n\n=== ''Play With Me'' (1994) ===\nStanding outside a Tokyo [[toy store]], Mori dressed herself as a cyborg\u2014with light blue hair in long ponytails, metallic blue hard-shell plastic top, silver plastic gloves, and a dress. Mori dresses similarly to the toys sold inside the store, while being ignored by the patrons who are entering to her left.<ref name=\"fineberg\">{{cite book|title=Art Since 1940. Strategies of Being|edition=Second|author=Fineberg, Jonathan|location=Upper Saddle, New Jersey|publisher=Prentice Hill Publishers|year=2000|pages=494\u20135|isbn=0-13-183978-0|type=paperback}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Subway'' (1994) ===\nMori stood in a [[Tokyo Subway|Tokyo subway]] car dressed as if she just landed from [[outer space]]. She was dressed in a silver metallic costume with a headset, microphone, and push-buttons on her forearm. This transformation\u2014along with Play With Me\u2014was to explore different constructed identities.<ref name=\"fineberg\" />\n\n=== ''Empty Dream'' (1995) ===\nMori manipulates a photo of a real public swimming place as she inserts herself in a blue plastic mermaid costume in several locations within the scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artdesigncafe.com/mariko-mori-artist-1999|title=Mariko Mori at Brooklyn Museum of Art (1999)|last=|first=|date=|website=ArtDesignCafe.com|publisher=World Sculpture News, 5(4)|pages=81-82|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> This image refers to, among other things, the rising of technology and philosophy around the creation of man through biotechnology.<ref name=\"fineberg\" /> This work was one of two by Mori that were featured at the 47th Venice Biennale (1997).<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== ''Oneness'' (2003) ===\nOneness, which was first exhibited at [[Deitch Projects]], New York, in 2003, is also the title of a group of six alien sculptures\u2014made from soft, skin-like material\u2014that hold each other\u2019s hands in a circle. They are sensitive to human touch, lighting up when hugged.  Oneness presents the dimensions of spirituality, photography and fashion into a deep look on the originality of the artist's skill hence the usage of technology's brand new trends. The outlook designs of Oneness gathers the capacity nevertheless the ability to use advanced technology knowledge converted to some sort of mystic and UFOs.<ref name=\"deitch\">[http://www.deitch.com/files/projects/Oneness.pdf Deitch Projects] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927190921/http://www.deitch.com/files/projects/Oneness.pdf |date=2011-09-27 }}</ref>\n\nIncluding in ''Oneness'' you can find some sub-works such as the ''Wave-UFO'', a 6.000&nbsp;kg dome where the visitor, once inside it, can see projected paintings reworked with computer graphics and then transformed into photographs in the interior dome of the Wave UFO.<ref name=\"deitch\" /> Conceptualization and prototyping of the Wave UFO was realized during Mori's residency at Eyebeam Art+Technology Center in Chelsea, New York.<ref name=\"eyebeam\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.eyebeam.org/projects/wave-ufo |title=Wave UFO at Eyebeam |access-date=2012-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202152823/http://www.eyebeam.org/projects/wave-ufo |archive-date=2014-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Rebirth'' ===\n''Rebirth'' is an exhibition from works spanning a number of years that was first shown in London at the [[Royal Academy of Art]] in 2012 and came to Japan Society in New York City in 2013.<ref name=\"NYTrebirth\"/> It is seen as a major departure from her previous work in that has far less to do with contemporary media and influences. One such example in this collection is ''Flat Stones'' (2006), which is a collection of ceramic rocks arranged similarly to a Jomon archaeological site.<ref name=\"NYTrebirth\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/11/arts/design/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori-at-japan-society.html|title=A Turnabout From Manga to Zen \u2018Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori,\u2019 at Japan Society|last=Rosenberg|first=Karen|date=October 10, 2013|work=New York Times|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> Mori also took inspiration from ancient Celtic practices, notably the stone circles in her ''Transcircle 1.1'' (2004), a group of [[LED lamp|LED]] lit columns that periodically shift color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://streamingmuseum.org/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori/|title=Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori|last=|first=|date=2013|website=Streaming Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Such engagement with prehistoric cultures derive from her search for universal values shared by humanity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ocula.com/artists/mariko-mori/|title=\"Mariko Mori\"|last=Paik|first=Sherry|date=|website=Ocula|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Faou Foundation==\nIn 2010, Mori founded a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization, the [[Faou Foundation]], (the word \"faou\" is a [[neologism]] created by Mori meaning \"eternal light\").<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Indrisek|first=Scott|date=May 2011|title=Crystal Flag: Mariko Mori Wants To Bring Her Nature-Loving Art To Six Continents|url=http://prod-images.exhibit-e.com/www_skny_com/MM_2011_05_Modern_Painters.pdf|journal=Modern Painters|doi=|pmid=|access-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faoufoundation.org/about/|title=Faou Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=Faou|publisher=|access-date=March 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315191037/http://faoufoundation.org/about/|archive-date=March 15, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Mori is listed as founder and president of the organization. Inspired by Buddhism and ecology, the Faou Foundation's mission is to create six art installations around the world as homages to the natural environment of each locale.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* 1997 \u2013 Menzione d\u2019onore, for her work Nirvana (1997), [[Venice Biennale]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sculpture.org/documents/scmag15/nov_15/nov15_features6.shtml|title=The Oneness of an Endless Universe: A Conversation with Mariko Mori|last=Castro|first=Jan Garden|date=November 2015|website=Sculpture Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n* 2001 \u2013 8th Annual Award as a \"Promising Artist and Scholar in the Field of Contemporary Japanese Art\", Japan Cultural Arts Foundation<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* {{Cite book|title=Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori|last=Tezuka|first=Miwako|last2=Sakurai|first2=Motoatsu|work=Exhibition Book|publisher=Japan Society|year=2013|isbn=978-0300196887|location=|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Mariko Mori: Wave UFO|last=Eccles|first=Tom|last2=Schneider|first2=Eckhard|last3=Mori|first3=Mariko|work=Exhibition Book|publisher=Kunsthaus Bregenz|year=2004|isbn=978-3883757216|location=Bregenz, Austria|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Mariko Mori \u2013\u00a0Dream Temple|last=Celant|first=Germano|last2=Nakazawa|first2=Shin Ichi|last3=Mori|first3=Mariko|work=Exhibition Book|publisher=Fondazione Prada|year=1999|isbn=978-8887029116|location=Milan, Italy|pages=}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*Video: [http://artistproject.metmuseum.org/2/mariko-mori/ The Artist Project: Mariko Mori on Botticelli's The Annunciation] from The Met\n*[http://streamingmuseum.org/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori/ Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori] at Streaming Museum\n* Her sculpture [http://www.tokyoartbeat.com/event/2006/6BE4.en Tom Na H-iu], driven by the [[Super-Kamiokande]] neutrino observatory\n* [http://www.artdesigncafe.com/Mariko-Mori-Charlotte-Kotik-Brooklyn-Museum-of-Art-1999 Mariko Mori at Brooklyn Museum of Art: Review of exhibition ''Empty Dream''], ''Asian Art News'', November 1999\n* [http://www.fondazioneprada.org/exibition/mariko-mori-dream-temple/?lang=en Mariko Mori: Dream Temple, 22 May \u2013 15 Jun 1999, Fondazione Prada, Milan, Italy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150224194558/http://desarthe.com/exhibitions/mariko-mori-flatstone/ Mariko Mori, Flatstone, exhibition, 28 March - 27 April 2013, de Sarthe Gallery, Hong Kong]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mori, Mariko}}\n[[Category:Japanese contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Japanese video artists]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Chelsea College of Arts]]\n[[Category:Japanese women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n[[Category:Buddhist artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Japanese volleyball player|Mariko Mori (volleyball)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Mariko Mori <br> \u68ee \u4e07\u91cc\u5b50\n| image = Mori Mariko at the Japan Society Panel on Art & Nature 2010.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| caption = Mariko Mori at the Japan Society Panel on Art & Nature on 2010\n| birth_name = \u68ee \u4e07\u91cc\u5b50\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|02|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| nationality = Japanese\n| spouse = \n| field = [[Photography]],  [[Digital art]], [[Sculpture]]\n| movement = Contemporary Art, Pop Art, Environmental Art\n| elected = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| alma_mater = [[Chelsea College of Art and Design]]\n| alt = Mariko Mori\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Mariko Mori'''|\u68ee \u4e07\u91cc\u5b50|Mori Mariko|born 1967}} is a Japanese [[Interdisciplinarity|multidisciplinary]] [[artist]]. She is known for her photographs and videos of her hybridized future self, often presented in various guises and featuring traditional Japanese motifs. Her work often explores themes of technology, spirituality and transcendence. \n\nIn 2010, she founded the [[Faou Foundation]], an art nonprofit based in New York City.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMariko Mori was born in Tokyo, Japan in 1967.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/Magazine/features/itoi/itoi11-20-01.asp|title=artnet.com Magazine Reviews - Tea with Mariko|last=Itoi|first=Kay|date=2001-11-20|website=Artnet.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05|quote=born in 1967, you are from one of the world's wealthiest families but you have never publicly spoken about it.}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/Mariko-Mori|title=Art Collection Online: Mariko Mori|last=|first=|date=|website=The Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artistproject.metmuseum.org/2/mariko-mori/|title=The Artist Project: Mariko Mori on Botticelli's The Annunciation|last=|first=|date=|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-04|quote=Mariko Mori, born in 1967, is a Japanese multidisciplinary artist interested in history and science. She is based in London, New York, and Tokyo.}}</ref> She comes from a wealthy family; her father is an inventor and technician, and her mother is an art historian of European Art.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.widewalls.ch/artist/mariko-mori/|title=Mariko Mori|website=Widewalls|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> \n\nWhile studying at [[Bunka Fashion College]] in Tokyo in the late 1980s, Mori worked as a [[fashion model]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jca-online.com/mori.html|title=Mariko Mori Interview|last=Sugiura|first=Kuni\u00e9|date=|website=www.jca-online.com|publisher=Journal of Contemporary Art, Inc|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05|quote=Mori: That originates from when I was a fashion model, at around age sixteen. Often I designed my own cloths and made them myself (I studied at a fashion college)}}</ref> In 1989, she moved to [[London]] to study at [[Byam Shaw School of Art]] and the [[Chelsea College of Art and Design]], she studied there until she graduated in 1992.<ref>Hallmark, Kara Kelley. 2007. Encyclopedia of Asian American artists. Westport, Conn: Greenwood Press. p. 129.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artandculture.com/artists/mariko-mori/|title=Mariko Mori|website=Art+Culture Projects|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> After graduating, she moved to New York City and participated in the [[Whitney Independent Study Program]] at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-may-27-ca-53666-story.html|title='Nirvana' Via Spectacle|date=1998-05-27|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMori's early work references traditional Japanese culture and ancient history but is characterized by futuristic themes and characters. Her early photography is heavily influenced by [[cosplay]]. Fantastic deities, robots, alien creatures, and spaceships are featured in video and photography with the artist herself dressed up in various self-made costumes as these characters.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Holzwarth|first1=Hans W.|title=100 Contemporary Artists A-Z|date=2009|publisher=Taschen|location=K\u00f6ln|isbn=978-3-8365-1490-3|pages=386\u2013391|edition=Taschen's 25th anniversary special}}</ref>\n\nPresent throughout her career is a fascination with technology and spirituality, with technology as a means of transcending and transforming consciousness and self.\n\nMori's early works, such as her photograph ''Play with Me'' (1994), use her own body as the subject, and she costumes herself as a sexualized, technological alien woman in everyday scenes. While her tableaus are fantastic and futuristic, the role played by the female characters she portrayed were often traditional, gendered roles such as a waitress in ''Tea Ceremony'' (1995), a futuristic version of the female Buddhist deity [[Kissh\u014dten|Kichijoten]] in ''Pure Land'' (1996-1998), or a female Japanese pop star in ''Birth of a Star.'' \n\nMori attributes her fascination with consciousness and death to experiencing [[sleep paralysis]] in her early-twenties for several hours which left her unsure if she was alive or dead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kyotojournal.org/the-journal/culture-arts/synthetic-dreams-the-art-of-mariko-mori/|title=The Art of Mariko Mori {{!}} Kyoto Journal|website=www.kyotojournal.org|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe juxtaposition of Eastern mythology with Western culture is a common theme in Mori's works, often through layering photography and digital imaging,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carnegiemuseums.org/cmag/bk_issue/1998/julaug/feat5.htm|title=Mariko Mori and Salvador Dali|last=Wilson|first=Ellen S.|date=July 1998|website=Carnegie Magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618000008/http://www.carnegiemuseums.org/cmag/bk_issue/1998/julaug/feat5.htm|archive-date=2008-06-18|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> such as in her 1995 installation ''Birth of a Star.'' Later works, such as ''Nirvana'' show her as a goddess, transcending her early roles via technology and image, and abandoning realistic urban scenes for more alien landscapes.\n\nAt the [[47th Venice Biennale]] (1997), Mori had two works exhibited at two different places, a photo collage titled, Empty Dream (1995) shown in the Japanese Pavillon, and the 3-D video installation, Nirvana (1997) which was shown in the Nordic Pavillon.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hz-journal.org/n4/borggreen.html|title=Hz #4 - Japan in Scandinavia|last=Borggreen|first=Gunhild|date=|website=www.hz-journal.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\nMori's work is featured in many public museum collections, including [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]],<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (LACMA),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/211751|title=Esoteric Cosmos|last=|first=|date=|website=LACMA Collections|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcachicago.org/Collection/Items/1995/Mariko-Mori-Birth-Of-A-Star-1995|title=Mariko Mori, Birth of a Star, 1995|website=MCA|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> and others.\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is married to composer Ken Ikeda.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/11/arts/design/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori-at-japan-society.html|title=A Turnabout From Manga to Zen|last=Rosenberg|first=Karen|date=2013-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> They have created collaborative work together, with Ikeda composing music and/or sound for many of Mori's pieces.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Work ==\n\n=== ''Play With Me'' (1994) ===\nStanding outside a Tokyo [[toy store]], Mori dressed herself as a cyborg\u2014with light blue hair in long ponytails, metallic blue hard-shell plastic top, silver plastic gloves, and a dress. Mori dresses similarly to the toys sold inside the store, while being ignored by the patrons who are entering to her left.<ref name=\"fineberg\">{{cite book|title=Art Since 1940. Strategies of Being|edition=Second|author=Fineberg, Jonathan|location=Upper Saddle, New Jersey|publisher=Prentice Hill Publishers|year=2000|pages=494\u20135|isbn=0-13-183978-0|type=paperback}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Subway'' (1994) ===\nMori stood in a [[Tokyo Subway|Tokyo subway]] car dressed as if she just landed from [[outer space]]. She was dressed in a silver metallic costume with a headset, microphone, and push-buttons on her forearm. This transformation\u2014along with Play With Me\u2014was to explore different constructed identities.<ref name=\"fineberg\" />\n\n=== ''Empty Dream'' (1995) ===\nMori manipulates a photo of a real public swimming place as she inserts herself in a blue plastic mermaid costume in several locations within the scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artdesigncafe.com/mariko-mori-artist-1999|title=Mariko Mori at Brooklyn Museum of Art (1999)|last=|first=|date=|website=ArtDesignCafe.com|publisher=World Sculpture News, 5(4)|pages=81-82|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> This image refers to, among other things, the rising of technology and philosophy around the creation of man through biotechnology.<ref name=\"fineberg\" /> This work was one of two by Mori that were featured at the 47th Venice Biennale (1997).<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== ''Oneness'' (2003) ===\nOneness, which was first exhibited at [[Deitch Projects]], New York, in 2003, is also the title of a group of six alien sculptures\u2014made from soft, skin-like material\u2014that hold each other\u2019s hands in a circle. They are sensitive to human touch, lighting up when hugged.  Oneness presents the dimensions of spirituality, photography and fashion into a deep look on the originality of the artist's skill hence the usage of technology's brand new trends. The outlook designs of Oneness gathers the capacity nevertheless the ability to use advanced technology knowledge converted to some sort of mystic and UFOs.<ref name=\"deitch\">[http://www.deitch.com/files/projects/Oneness.pdf Deitch Projects] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927190921/http://www.deitch.com/files/projects/Oneness.pdf |date=2011-09-27 }}</ref>\n\nIncluding in ''Oneness'' you can find some sub-works such as the ''Wave-UFO'', a 6.000&nbsp;kg dome where the visitor, once inside it, can see projected paintings reworked with computer graphics and then transformed into photographs in the interior dome of the Wave UFO.<ref name=\"deitch\" /> Conceptualization and prototyping of the Wave UFO was realized during Mori's residency at Eyebeam Art+Technology Center in Chelsea, New York.<ref name=\"eyebeam\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.eyebeam.org/projects/wave-ufo |title=Wave UFO at Eyebeam |access-date=2012-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202152823/http://www.eyebeam.org/projects/wave-ufo |archive-date=2014-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Rebirth'' ===\n''Rebirth'' is an exhibition from works spanning a number of years that was first shown in London at the [[Royal Academy of Art]] in 2012 and came to Japan Society in New York City in 2013.<ref name=\"NYTrebirth\"/> It is seen as a major departure from her previous work in that has far less to do with contemporary media and influences. One such example in this collection is ''Flat Stones'' (2006), which is a collection of ceramic rocks arranged similarly to a Jomon archaeological site.<ref name=\"NYTrebirth\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/11/arts/design/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori-at-japan-society.html|title=A Turnabout From Manga to Zen \u2018Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori,\u2019 at Japan Society|last=Rosenberg|first=Karen|date=October 10, 2013|work=New York Times|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> Mori also took inspiration from ancient Celtic practices, notably the stone circles in her ''Transcircle 1.1'' (2004), a group of [[LED lamp|LED]] lit columns that periodically shift color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://streamingmuseum.org/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori/|title=Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori|last=|first=|date=2013|website=Streaming Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Such engagement with prehistoric cultures derive from her search for universal values shared by humanity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ocula.com/artists/mariko-mori/|title=\"Mariko Mori\"|last=Paik|first=Sherry|date=|website=Ocula|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Faou Foundation==\nIn 2010, Mori founded a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization, the [[Faou Foundation]], (the word \"faou\" is a [[neologism]] created by Mori meaning \"eternal light\").<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Indrisek|first=Scott|date=May 2011|title=Crystal Flag: Mariko Mori Wants To Bring Her Nature-Loving Art To Six Continents|url=http://prod-images.exhibit-e.com/www_skny_com/MM_2011_05_Modern_Painters.pdf|journal=Modern Painters|doi=|pmid=|access-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faoufoundation.org/about/|title=Faou Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=Faou|publisher=|access-date=March 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315191037/http://faoufoundation.org/about/|archive-date=March 15, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Mori is listed as founder and president of the organization. Inspired by Buddhism and ecology, the Faou Foundation's mission is to create six art installations around the world as homages to the natural environment of each locale.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* 1997 \u2013 Menzione d\u2019onore, for her work Nirvana (1997), [[Venice Biennale]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sculpture.org/documents/scmag15/nov_15/nov15_features6.shtml|title=The Oneness of an Endless Universe: A Conversation with Mariko Mori|last=Castro|first=Jan Garden|date=November 2015|website=Sculpture Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n* 2001 \u2013 8th Annual Award as a \"Promising Artist and Scholar in the Field of Contemporary Japanese Art\", Japan Cultural Arts Foundation<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* {{Cite book|title=Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori|last=Tezuka|first=Miwako|last2=Sakurai|first2=Motoatsu|work=Exhibition Book|publisher=Japan Society|year=2013|isbn=978-0300196887|location=|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Mariko Mori: Wave UFO|last=Eccles|first=Tom|last2=Schneider|first2=Eckhard|last3=Mori|first3=Mariko|work=Exhibition Book|publisher=Kunsthaus Bregenz|year=2004|isbn=978-3883757216|location=Bregenz, Austria|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Mariko Mori \u2013\u00a0Dream Temple|last=Celant|first=Germano|last2=Nakazawa|first2=Shin Ichi|last3=Mori|first3=Mariko|work=Exhibition Book|publisher=Fondazione Prada|year=1999|isbn=978-8887029116|location=Milan, Italy|pages=}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*Video: [http://artistproject.metmuseum.org/2/mariko-mori/ The Artist Project: Mariko Mori on Botticelli's The Annunciation] from The Met\n*[http://streamingmuseum.org/rebirth-recent-work-by-mariko-mori/ Rebirth: Recent Work by Mariko Mori] at Streaming Museum\n* Her sculpture [http://www.tokyoartbeat.com/event/2006/6BE4.en Tom Na H-iu], driven by the [[Super-Kamiokande]] neutrino observatory\n* [http://www.artdesigncafe.com/Mariko-Mori-Charlotte-Kotik-Brooklyn-Museum-of-Art-1999 Mariko Mori at Brooklyn Museum of Art: Review of exhibition ''Empty Dream''], ''Asian Art News'', November 1999\n* [http://www.fondazioneprada.org/exibition/mariko-mori-dream-temple/?lang=en Mariko Mori: Dream Temple, 22 May \u2013 15 Jun 1999, Fondazione Prada, Milan, Italy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150224194558/http://desarthe.com/exhibitions/mariko-mori-flatstone/ Mariko Mori, Flatstone, exhibition, 28 March - 27 April 2013, de Sarthe Gallery, Hong Kong]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mori, Mariko}}\n[[Category:Japanese contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Japanese video artists]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Chelsea College of Arts]]\n[[Category:Japanese women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n[[Category:Buddhist artists]]\n", "name_user": "Badabara", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariko_Mori"}
